RM <- lm(points ~ gender + attitude +  stra, data = mydata)
summary(RM)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ gender + attitude + stra, data = mydata)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.7179  -3.3285   0.5343   3.7412  10.9007 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   8.9798     2.4030   3.737 0.000258 ***
## genderM      -0.2236     0.9248  -0.242 0.809231    
## attitude      3.5100     0.5956   5.893 2.13e-08 ***
## stra          0.8911     0.5441   1.638 0.103419    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.304 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2051, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1904 
## F-statistic: 13.93 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 3.982e-08

here points is the target or dependent variable. gender,attitude and stra are the independent or explanatory variable. Here, Multiple R-squared value is 0.2051 which means about 21% variation in points can be explained by our model (explained by gender, attitude and stra). Here, by F-statistics and p-value we can know the overall significance of our model. By the Residual standard error we can know how much differences in observed and predicted value of target variable(points).we found estimate value of Intercept is 8.9798, which meand the value of points is 8.9798 when all the value of explanatory variables are 0. estimate value of gender is -0.2236, which means for 1year increase in gender, points decrease by 0.2236. Although here p-value is very high and we can say that there is no relationship between gender and points.

In our model only attitude is highly significant. Gender has the least significance among three values. so, let’s try removing gender from our model

5

plot(RM)

assumption of model: linear relationship, multivariate normality, Homoscedasticity. we can use diagnostic plots to find the assumption of the regression model. From the Residuals vs Fitted plots linearity can be tested between two variables.Here, from the plot we can see that in the x axis Fitted values of points while Residuals in the y axis. there is a flat red line which means linear relationship between fitted values and residuals and variation is constant. from the Normal Q-Q plot we can check, are the variables normanly distributed or not. Here, we can see a diagonal line in the plot. which means our residuals values are normaly distributed. Residuals vs Levarage plot also used for test the linearity. Here, flat red line indicate linea relationship.

  1. The above data is about alcohol consumption in two Portugese school students. The data has 380 rows and 36 columns. Or, in other way it has 35 variables. The data set modeled under binary classification

  2. I am choosing 4 random variables namely age, failures, health and freetime as explanatory variables and high_use as a target variables. I am assuming that there is a strong positive correlation between high_use with each variables.

5.Let,s now fit the logistic regression model.

lr <- glm(high_use ~ age + failures + health + freetime, data = mydata, family = "binomial")
summary(lr)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = high_use ~ age + failures + health + freetime, 
##     family = "binomial", data = mydata)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.5762  -0.8459  -0.7152   1.2772   1.9947  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)   
## (Intercept) -5.22299    1.77664  -2.940  0.00328 **
## age          0.17751    0.10032   1.769  0.07683 . 
## failures     0.42475    0.18992   2.236  0.02532 * 
## health       0.07152    0.08464   0.845  0.39813   
## freetime     0.32324    0.12060   2.680  0.00736 **
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 465.68  on 381  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 445.66  on 377  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 455.66
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

Deviance residuals, which are a measure of model fit. It shows the distribution of the deviance residuals for individual cases used in the model. From the model we can see that failures and freetime has the most significant relationship with alcohol use.

The logistic regression coefficients give the change in the log odds of the outcome for a one unit increase in the predictor variable. For every one unit change in age, the log odds of alcohol use increases by 0.17.

coef(lr)
## (Intercept)         age    failures      health    freetime 
## -5.22298692  0.17751209  0.42474936  0.07152038  0.32323750
OR <- coef(lr) %>% exp
CI <- confint(lr) %>% exp
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
cbind(OR,CI)
##                      OR        2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.005391202 0.0001553233 0.1672625
## age         1.194242493 0.9824070268 1.4570567
## failures    1.529207098 1.0558532403 2.2359959
## health      1.074140041 0.9113104069 1.2708920
## freetime    1.381593441 1.0939258330 1.7569297

from the odd ratios failures has the highest odd ratio(1.53) with 95% confidence interval(1.05 to 2.23) compare to freetime, age and heath. Which means for a one unit increase in failures, the odds of alcohol consumption increase by a factor of 1.53 and in 95% occasion it is true. Lets, remove age and health from the model and fil the model again

  1. 2*2 cross tabulation of predictions versus the actual values

mydata <- mutate(mydata, probability = probabilities)

## high_use FALSE TRUE  Sum
##    FALSE  0.68 0.02 0.70
##    TRUE   0.28 0.02 0.30
##    Sum    0.96 0.04 1.00
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = mydata$high_use, prob = mydata$probability)
## [1] 0.3010471

  1. so , about 30% of observation incorrectly classified. while, the todal loss prediction is 100. comparative performance If, we would take low_use(FALSE for alcohol use is greater than 2) instead of high_use we would get 70% incorrect classified observation.

  2. bonus

library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = mydata, cost = loss_func, glmfit = lr2, K = 10)
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.3089005

With 10-fold cross-validation the prediction error is around 0.30. which is higherer than in the data camp exercise.

After scaling the data, from the summary of scaled data we can see data as a standarized data. we can see minimum and maximun value of a variable, as well as mean, median and quarter of every column(variable).

lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
